Improve change point detection reliability (#10) _nl_  _nl_ Improve change point detection reliability _nl_  _nl_ We noticed that EDivisive algorithm is unreliable _nl_ if run on a very long series of data with many _nl_ cancelling changes. If a regression is present for _nl_ a short time, the time may be too short in proportion _nl_ to the length of the entire signal, it may be missed. _nl_  _nl_ This commit modifies the way how EDivisive algorithm _nl_ is applied to our data. Instead of running it on _nl_ a full series, we apply it to a shorter window _nl_ moving over the data. This way the amount of data _nl_ per each invocation of EDivisive is smaller and _nl_ it can see fewer change points at a time _nl_ making it more reliable. _nl_  _nl_ A nice bonus side effect is that this _nl_ reduces the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n k^2) _nl_ where k window size, n length of the series. _nl_

Switch to T-test for significance testing _nl_  _nl_ Student's T-Test has the following advantages _nl_ over QHat Permutation Tester: _nl_  _nl_ - repeatability, lack of randomness _nl_ - an order of magnitude higher performance _nl_  _nl_ Additionally this commit adds Mann-Whitney based _nl_ significance tester implementation for future _nl_ evaluation. _nl_  _nl_ Fixes #14 _nl_

Remove change points with small change magnitude _nl_  _nl_ This commit adds a change-point post-processing step. _nl_ In that step, weak change-points are removed based on _nl_ their p-value and change magnitude. This allows us _nl_ to bump up the p-value limit in the e-divisive _nl_ part of the algorithm, potentially reducing the risk _nl_ of missing some points. In Edivisive, change points _nl_ to found later typically increase the p-value of _nl_ change-points found earlier; hence the algorithm can _nl_ miss some good points. _nl_  _nl_ Fixes #25 _nl_

Refactoring: Extract ComparativeStats from ChangePoint _nl_  _nl_ We need to describe a result of comparing _nl_ two time series with each other. _nl_ This need also arises when describing a change point. _nl_ However the ChangePoint class doesn't make much sense _nl_ for describing comparison between two series, because it contains _nl_ additional properties like index, time, etc. _nl_

Remove dependency on fallout (#60) _nl_  _nl_ Remove dependency on fallout _nl_  _nl_ The biggest change introduced in this commit is moving the test _nl_ configuration into hunter.yaml file. This way the results of tests _nl_ launched from systems other than Fallout can be analyzed, as long as _nl_ they send data to Graphite. Previously contacting Fallout was needed to _nl_ fetch the export prefix of the test, but now all the required _nl_ information is located in the config file. _nl_  _nl_ Ad-hoc (command-line) test configuration has been removed. A test must _nl_ be defined in the config file before it can be analyzed. This simplifies _nl_ hunter a lot and although it may initially feel a bit less _nl_ user-friendly, having a single way of passing test metadata to hunter _nl_ makes it easier to reason about. If this turns out to be too limiting, _nl_ we may add a way to submit config files (or override config file _nl_ properties) from the command line in the future. _nl_  _nl_ Unifying configuration allowed the `analyze` and `bulk-analyze` _nl_ commands to be merged into a single `analyze` command which accepts a _nl_ list of test names or test group names. _nl_  _nl_ Reduce the length of the target query in Graphite

Extract change point analysis results as AnalyzedSeries class _nl_  _nl_ Returning a vector of change points is not good enough, because _nl_ in some cases we want to process change points one metric at a time, _nl_ so we want them to be grouped by metric name, not time. _nl_  _nl_ Additionally, this makes code for comparing two time series _nl_ or comparing different time points in a single series cleaner, _nl_ because the client code doesn't need to compute and store _nl_ change points in additional variables. _nl_

New command: hunter regressions _nl_  _nl_ The regressions command compares the performance of the _nl_ end of the selected range with the performance at the beginning _nl_ of the selected range. _nl_  _nl_ E.g. hunter regressions <test> --since '10 weeks ago' compares _nl_ the current average performance level with the average performance about _nl_ 10 weeks ago. If current performance is worse significantly (in terms _nl_ of statistical significance) than the baseline performance on any of _nl_ the metrics, it is reported to stdout. _nl_  _nl_ Fixes #13 _nl_

Grafana annotation support redesign (#80) _nl_  _nl_ Grafana annotation redesign _nl_  _nl_ Grafana annotations are no longer pushed individually to each panel. _nl_ Now they are pushed into a global annotation list and appropriately _nl_ tagged. This removed a lot of complexity and also speeded up annotation _nl_ updates by several factors. _nl_  _nl_ The test/metric annotation tags are configurable _nl_ in the config file thanks to a new property 'annotate'. _nl_  _nl_ A new command `hunter remove-annotations` has been added _nl_ to remove annotations.

Finding regressions on a feature branch _nl_  _nl_ A new configuration property has been added to graphite _nl_ tests: `branch_prefix`. _nl_  _nl_ If the user specifies `--branch <name>` argument, the data _nl_ are fetched from the prefix set in `branch_prefix`. _nl_ This works for both `analyze` and `regressions` commands. _nl_  _nl_ The `regressions` command has been modified to compare _nl_ performance of the branch selected with `--branch` to the _nl_ baseline taken from the main branch, located by the main prefix. _nl_

Replace psycopg2-binary with pg8000 and black with ruff (#25) _nl_  _nl_ * Replace psycopg2-binary with pg8000 _nl_  _nl_ psycopg2 is licensed under LGPL that's not compatible with ASF - _nl_ https://www.apache.org/legal/resolved.html#category-x _nl_  _nl_ * Replace black with ruff _nl_  _nl_ black depends on pathspec that is licensed under MPL 2.0. Even though _nl_ MPL 2.0 can _maybe_ be included in an ASF project, I'd _nl_ prefer to simplify the discussion and just replace black with ruff that _nl_ is licensed as Apache 2.0, does not have any dependencies, and is _nl_ already used by other Apache projects.

Fix: When computing weak changepoints, keep p-value below 1 _nl_  _nl_ Hunter modified e-divisive such that it first does a pass using a _nl_ higher p-value, then filters out all change points that have a _nl_ higher p-value than the actual max_pvalue specified by the user. _nl_  _nl_ The initial higher pvalue is max_pvalue * 10. This means that _nl_ for values higher than 0.1, the first pvalue is > 1.0. This _nl_ doesn't make sense. In fact 1.0 also doesn't make sense because _nl_ now every point is a weak change point. _nl_  _nl_ This patch modifies the call to split() such that: _nl_  max_pvalue:   first pass pvalue _nl_  0.0 - 0.05:   max_pvalue * 10 (unchanged) _nl_  0.0 - 0.5 :   max_pvalue * 2 _nl_  0.5 - 1.0 :   max_pvalue _nl_  _nl_ Since values above  0.1 didn't really make sense before this patch, _nl_ the area where this could cause changes is for users using max_pvalue _nl_ between 0.05 and 0.1. The merge() phase should however eventually produce _nl_ approximately the same set of change points anyway, but this isn't _nl_ guaranteed. _nl_

Optimization: Incremental Hunter _nl_  _nl_ The common case is to add new data points to the end of the series. _nl_ In this case we don't need to recompute all change points, we can _nl_ just compute window_len points from the end. We do roughly _nl_ 2 * window_len for good measure. _nl_
